1
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:12,995
As you can probably tell by now the

2
00:00:12,995 --> 00:00:15,235
bulk of this series is on understanding matrix

3
00:00:15,235 --> 00:00:17,795
and vector operations through that more visual lens

4
00:00:17,795 --> 00:00:19,715
of linear transformations.

5
00:00:19,955 --> 00:00:22,595
This video is no exception, describing the concepts

6
00:00:22,595 --> 00:00:26,035
of inverse matrices, column space, rank, and, null

7
00:00:26,035 --> 00:00:27,475
space through that lens.

8
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:30,480
A forewarning though, I'm not gonna talk about

9
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:32,800
the methods for actually computing these things, and

10
00:00:32,800 --> 00:00:35,040
some would argue that that's pretty important. There

11
00:00:35,040 --> 00:00:36,720
are a lot of very good resources for

12
00:00:36,720 --> 00:00:40,000
learning those methods outside this series. Keywords, Gaussian

13
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,005
elimination and row echelon form. I think most

14
00:00:43,005 --> 00:00:44,525
of the value that I actually have to

15
00:00:44,525 --> 00:00:46,685
add here is on the intuition half.

16
00:00:46,925 --> 00:00:49,245
Plus, in practice, we usually get software to

17
00:00:49,245 --> 00:00:50,845
compute this stuff for us anyway.

18
00:00:51,405 --> 00:00:53,245
First, a few words on the usefulness of

19
00:00:53,245 --> 00:00:55,420
linear algebra. By now you already have a

20
00:00:55,420 --> 00:00:57,100
hint for how it's used in describing the

21
00:00:57,100 --> 00:00:59,420
manipulation of space, which is useful for things

22
00:00:59,420 --> 00:01:01,340
like computer graphics and robotics.

23
00:01:01,500 --> 00:01:03,100
But one of the main reasons that linear

24
00:01:03,100 --> 00:01:05,980
algebra is more broadly applicable and required for

25
00:01:05,980 --> 00:01:08,285
just about any technical discipline is that it

26
00:01:08,285 --> 00:01:10,765
lets us solve certain systems of equations.

27
00:01:11,325 --> 00:01:13,565
When I say system of equations, I mean

28
00:01:13,565 --> 00:01:15,325
you have a list of variables, things you

29
00:01:15,325 --> 00:01:17,485
don't know, and a list of equations relating

30
00:01:17,485 --> 00:01:18,045
them.

31
00:01:18,365 --> 00:01:19,725
In a lot of situations,

32
00:01:19,725 --> 00:01:21,645
those equations can get very complicated.

33
00:01:22,150 --> 00:01:24,230
But if you're lucky, they might take on

34
00:01:24,230 --> 00:01:25,590
a certain special form.

35
00:01:26,390 --> 00:01:27,830
Within each equation,

36
00:01:27,990 --> 00:01:30,070
the only thing happening to each variable is

37
00:01:30,070 --> 00:01:32,230
that it's scaled by some constant,

38
00:01:32,390 --> 00:01:33,910
and the only thing happening to each of

39
00:01:33,910 --> 00:01:36,310
those scaled variables is that they're added to

40
00:01:36,310 --> 00:01:36,630
each other.

41
00:01:37,475 --> 00:01:40,595
So no exponents or fancy functions are multiplying

42
00:01:40,595 --> 00:01:42,515
two variables together, things like that.

43
00:01:43,395 --> 00:01:45,235
The typical way to organize this sort of

44
00:01:45,235 --> 00:01:47,395
special system of equations is to throw all

45
00:01:47,395 --> 00:01:48,835
the variables on the left

46
00:01:49,730 --> 00:01:52,450
and put any lingering constants on the right.

47
00:01:53,810 --> 00:01:55,810
It's also nice to vertically line up the

48
00:01:55,810 --> 00:01:57,570
common variables, and to do that, you might

49
00:01:57,570 --> 00:01:59,650
need to throw in some zero coefficients whenever

50
00:01:59,650 --> 00:02:01,410
the variable doesn't show up in one of

51
00:02:01,410 --> 00:02:01,970
the equations.

52
00:02:04,705 --> 00:02:07,505
This is called a linear system of equations.

53
00:02:08,065 --> 00:02:09,665
You might notice that this looks a lot

54
00:02:09,665 --> 00:02:11,505
like matrix vector multiplication.

55
00:02:11,905 --> 00:02:13,825
In fact, you can package all of the

56
00:02:13,825 --> 00:02:17,280
equations together into a single vector equation where

57
00:02:17,280 --> 00:02:19,280
you have the matrix containing all of the

58
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:21,840
constant coefficients and a vector containing all of

59
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:22,720
the variables,

60
00:02:22,960 --> 00:02:25,920
and their matrix vector product equals some different

61
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:27,120
constant vector.

62
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:31,575
Let's name that constant matrix A, denote the

63
00:02:31,575 --> 00:02:33,895
vector holding the variables with a bold faced

64
00:02:33,895 --> 00:02:34,695
x,

65
00:02:34,775 --> 00:02:36,375
and call the constant vector on the right

66
00:02:36,375 --> 00:02:37,895
hand side v.

67
00:02:38,775 --> 00:02:40,775
This is more than just a notational trick

68
00:02:40,775 --> 00:02:42,535
to get our system of equations written on

69
00:02:42,535 --> 00:02:44,540
one line. It sheds light on a pretty

70
00:02:44,540 --> 00:02:47,100
cool geometric interpretation for the problem.

71
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:50,460
The matrix A corresponds with some linear transformation.

72
00:02:50,620 --> 00:02:53,260
So solving A x equals v means we're

73
00:02:53,260 --> 00:02:54,780
looking for a vector x,

74
00:02:54,860 --> 00:02:56,780
which after applying the transformation

75
00:02:56,780 --> 00:02:57,980
lands on v.

76
00:03:00,165 --> 00:03:02,085
Think about what's happening here for a moment.

77
00:03:02,085 --> 00:03:04,005
You can hold in your head this really

78
00:03:04,005 --> 00:03:07,365
complicated idea of multiple variables all intermingling with

79
00:03:07,365 --> 00:03:09,605
each other just by thinking about squishing and

80
00:03:09,605 --> 00:03:11,525
morphing space and trying to figure out which

81
00:03:11,525 --> 00:03:13,765
vector lands on another. Cool, right?

82
00:03:14,720 --> 00:03:16,400
To start simple, let's say you have a

83
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:18,720
system with two equations and two unknowns.

84
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:20,720
This means the matrix A is a two

85
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:22,800
by two matrix and v and x are

86
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:24,320
each two dimensional vectors.

87
00:03:25,520 --> 00:03:27,600
Now, how we think about the solutions to

88
00:03:27,600 --> 00:03:30,845
this equation depends on whether the transformation associated

89
00:03:30,845 --> 00:03:33,325
with a squishes all of space into a

90
00:03:33,325 --> 00:03:35,485
lower dimension like a line or a point,

91
00:03:35,725 --> 00:03:37,645
or if it leaves everything spanning the full

92
00:03:37,645 --> 00:03:38,925
two dimensions where it started.

93
00:03:40,540 --> 00:03:42,540
In the language of the last video, we

94
00:03:42,540 --> 00:03:44,700
subdivide into the cases where A has zero

95
00:03:44,700 --> 00:03:47,020
determinant and the case where A has non

96
00:03:47,020 --> 00:03:48,300
zero determinant.

97
00:03:51,340 --> 00:03:53,180
Let's start with the most likely case where

98
00:03:53,180 --> 00:03:55,765
the determinant is non zero, meaning space does

99
00:03:55,765 --> 00:03:58,085
not get squished into a zero area region.

100
00:03:58,565 --> 00:04:00,645
In this case, there will always be one

101
00:04:00,645 --> 00:04:03,285
and only one vector that lands on v

102
00:04:03,285 --> 00:04:04,965
and you can find it by playing the

103
00:04:04,965 --> 00:04:06,485
transformation in reverse.

104
00:04:07,045 --> 00:04:09,285
Following where v goes as we rewind the

105
00:04:09,285 --> 00:04:11,460
tape like this, you'll find the vector x

106
00:04:11,460 --> 00:04:13,780
such that a times x equals v.

107
00:04:15,700 --> 00:04:17,860
When you play the transformation in reverse, it

108
00:04:17,860 --> 00:04:21,220
actually corresponds to a separate linear transformation commonly

109
00:04:21,220 --> 00:04:24,020
called the inverse of a, denoted a to

110
00:04:24,020 --> 00:04:24,740
the negative one.

111
00:04:25,255 --> 00:04:27,815
For example, if A was a counterclockwise rotation

112
00:04:27,815 --> 00:04:30,215
by 90 degrees, then the inverse of A

113
00:04:30,215 --> 00:04:33,015
would be a clockwise rotation by 90 degrees.

114
00:04:34,615 --> 00:04:36,615
If A was a rightward shear that pushes

115
00:04:36,615 --> 00:04:38,510
j hat one unit to the right, the

116
00:04:38,510 --> 00:04:40,350
inverse of A would be a leftward shear

117
00:04:40,350 --> 00:04:42,190
that pushes j hat one unit to the

118
00:04:42,190 --> 00:04:42,750
left.

119
00:04:44,190 --> 00:04:47,070
In general, A inverse is the unique transformation

120
00:04:47,070 --> 00:04:48,990
with the property that if you first apply

121
00:04:48,990 --> 00:04:51,630
A, then follow it with the transformation A

122
00:04:51,630 --> 00:04:53,550
inverse, you end up back where you started.

123
00:04:54,455 --> 00:04:57,655
Applying one transformation after another is captured algebraically

124
00:04:57,655 --> 00:04:59,255
with matrix multiplication.

125
00:04:59,575 --> 00:05:01,895
So the core property of this transformation A

126
00:05:01,895 --> 00:05:05,095
inverse is that A inverse times A

127
00:05:05,255 --> 00:05:07,335
equals the matrix that corresponds to doing nothing.

128
00:05:07,970 --> 00:05:10,050
The transformation that does nothing is called the

129
00:05:10,050 --> 00:05:11,570
identity transformation.

130
00:05:11,810 --> 00:05:13,410
It leaves I hat and j hat each

131
00:05:13,410 --> 00:05:16,130
where they are, unmoved, so its columns are

132
00:05:16,130 --> 00:05:18,050
one zero and zero one.

133
00:05:19,985 --> 00:05:22,145
Once you find this inverse, which in practice

134
00:05:22,145 --> 00:05:23,425
you do with a computer,

135
00:05:23,585 --> 00:05:26,145
you can solve your equation by multiplying this

136
00:05:26,145 --> 00:05:28,065
inverse matrix by V.

137
00:05:29,905 --> 00:05:32,385
And again, what this means geometrically

138
00:05:32,490 --> 00:05:35,210
is that you're playing the transformation in reverse

139
00:05:35,210 --> 00:05:36,810
and following V.

140
00:05:40,330 --> 00:05:42,810
This non zero determinant case, which for a

141
00:05:42,810 --> 00:05:44,570
random choice of matrix is by far the

142
00:05:44,570 --> 00:05:46,855
most likely one, corresponds with the idea that

143
00:05:46,855 --> 00:05:49,575
if you have two unknowns and two equations,

144
00:05:49,575 --> 00:05:51,255
it's almost certainly the case that there's a

145
00:05:51,255 --> 00:05:52,695
single unique solution.

146
00:05:53,975 --> 00:05:55,975
This idea also makes sense in higher dimensions

147
00:05:55,975 --> 00:05:57,895
when the number of equations equals the number

148
00:05:57,895 --> 00:05:58,535
of unknowns.

149
00:05:59,390 --> 00:06:02,030
Again, the system of equations can be translated

150
00:06:02,030 --> 00:06:04,030
to the geometric interpretation

151
00:06:04,030 --> 00:06:06,350
where you have some transformation a

152
00:06:08,270 --> 00:06:10,750
and some vector v and you're looking for

153
00:06:10,750 --> 00:06:12,830
the vector x that lands on v.

154
00:06:16,045 --> 00:06:18,445
As long as the transformation A doesn't squish

155
00:06:18,445 --> 00:06:20,685
all of space into a lower dimension, meaning

156
00:06:20,685 --> 00:06:23,565
its determinant is non zero, there will be

157
00:06:23,565 --> 00:06:25,005
an inverse transformation,

158
00:06:25,005 --> 00:06:27,240
A inverse, with the property that if you

159
00:06:27,240 --> 00:06:29,800
first do A, then you do A inverse,

160
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:31,400
it's the same as doing nothing.

161
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:35,560
And to solve your equation, you just have

162
00:06:35,560 --> 00:06:38,840
to multiply that reverse transformation matrix by the

163
00:06:38,840 --> 00:06:39,560
vector v.

164
00:06:43,415 --> 00:06:45,735
But when the determinant is zero and the

165
00:06:45,735 --> 00:06:49,255
transformation associated with the system of equations squishes

166
00:06:49,255 --> 00:06:50,935
space into a smaller dimension,

167
00:06:51,255 --> 00:06:53,815
there is no inverse. You cannot un squish

168
00:06:53,815 --> 00:06:55,495
a line to turn it into a plane.

169
00:06:55,830 --> 00:06:57,590
At least that's not something that a function

170
00:06:57,590 --> 00:07:00,550
can do. That would require transforming each individual

171
00:07:00,550 --> 00:07:03,270
vector into a whole line full of vectors.

172
00:07:03,750 --> 00:07:05,750
But functions can only take a single input

173
00:07:05,750 --> 00:07:06,790
to a single output.

174
00:07:08,245 --> 00:07:09,045
Similarly,

175
00:07:09,045 --> 00:07:11,525
for three equations and three unknowns, there will

176
00:07:11,525 --> 00:07:14,325
be no inverse if the corresponding transformation

177
00:07:14,405 --> 00:07:17,045
squishes three d space onto the plane or

178
00:07:17,045 --> 00:07:18,565
even if it squishes it onto a line

179
00:07:18,565 --> 00:07:19,525
or a point.

180
00:07:19,925 --> 00:07:22,405
Those all correspond to a determinant of zero

181
00:07:22,260 --> 00:07:24,420
since any region is squished into something with

182
00:07:24,420 --> 00:07:25,460
zero volume.

183
00:07:26,900 --> 00:07:29,540
It's still possible that a solution exists even

184
00:07:29,540 --> 00:07:31,540
when there is no inverse. It's just that

185
00:07:31,540 --> 00:07:34,340
when your transformation squishes space onto, say, a

186
00:07:34,340 --> 00:07:36,545
line, you have to be lucky enough that

187
00:07:36,545 --> 00:07:39,665
the vector v lives somewhere on that line.

188
00:07:43,265 --> 00:07:45,025
You might notice that some of these zero

189
00:07:45,025 --> 00:07:47,985
determinant cases feel a lot more restrictive than

190
00:07:47,985 --> 00:07:50,305
others. Given a three by three matrix, for

191
00:07:50,305 --> 00:07:52,400
example, it seems a lot harder for a

192
00:07:52,400 --> 00:07:54,880
solution to exist when it squishes space onto

193
00:07:54,880 --> 00:07:57,200
a line compared to when it squishes things

194
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:59,120
onto a plane, even though both of those

195
00:07:59,120 --> 00:08:00,560
are zero determinant.

196
00:08:02,480 --> 00:08:04,160
We have some language that's a bit more

197
00:08:04,160 --> 00:08:06,080
specific than just saying zero determinant.

198
00:08:06,425 --> 00:08:08,585
When the output of a transformation is a

199
00:08:08,585 --> 00:08:10,825
line, meaning it's one dimensional,

200
00:08:10,825 --> 00:08:13,145
we say the transformation has a rank of

201
00:08:13,145 --> 00:08:13,785
one.

202
00:08:15,065 --> 00:08:16,985
If all the vectors land on some two

203
00:08:16,985 --> 00:08:19,465
dimensional plane, we say the transformation has a

204
00:08:19,465 --> 00:08:20,425
rank of two.

205
00:08:22,860 --> 00:08:25,020
So the word rank means the number of

206
00:08:25,020 --> 00:08:27,740
dimensions in the output of a transformation.

207
00:08:28,380 --> 00:08:29,900
For instance, in the case of two by

208
00:08:29,900 --> 00:08:32,220
two matrices, rank two is the best that

209
00:08:32,220 --> 00:08:34,540
it can be. It means the basis vectors

210
00:08:34,540 --> 00:08:37,055
continue to span the full two dimensions of

211
00:08:37,055 --> 00:08:39,695
space and the determinant is non zero. But

212
00:08:39,695 --> 00:08:41,295
for three by three matrices,

213
00:08:41,295 --> 00:08:43,375
rank two means that we've collapsed,

214
00:08:43,535 --> 00:08:44,735
but not as much as they would have

215
00:08:44,735 --> 00:08:46,655
collapsed for a rank one situation.

216
00:08:47,135 --> 00:08:48,415
If a three d transformation

217
00:08:48,660 --> 00:08:50,820
has a non zero determinant and its output

218
00:08:50,820 --> 00:08:52,740
fills all of three d space, it has

219
00:08:52,740 --> 00:08:53,780
a rank of three.

220
00:08:54,420 --> 00:08:56,500
This set of all possible outputs for your

221
00:08:56,500 --> 00:08:58,820
matrix, whether it's a line, a plane, three

222
00:08:58,820 --> 00:09:00,020
d space, whatever,

223
00:09:00,180 --> 00:09:02,740
is called the column space of your matrix.

224
00:09:04,205 --> 00:09:06,045
You can probably guess where that name comes

225
00:09:06,045 --> 00:09:08,685
from. The columns of your matrix tell you

226
00:09:08,685 --> 00:09:10,525
where the basis vectors land,

227
00:09:11,085 --> 00:09:13,965
and the span of those transformed basis vectors

228
00:09:14,045 --> 00:09:16,205
gives you all possible outputs.

229
00:09:16,525 --> 00:09:19,020
In other words, the column space is the

230
00:09:19,020 --> 00:09:21,500
span of the columns of your matrix.

231
00:09:23,580 --> 00:09:25,900
So a more precise definition of rank would

232
00:09:25,900 --> 00:09:27,980
be that it's the number of dimensions in

233
00:09:27,980 --> 00:09:28,940
the column space.

234
00:09:30,035 --> 00:09:31,635
When this rank is as high as it

235
00:09:31,635 --> 00:09:33,715
can be, meaning it equals the number of

236
00:09:33,715 --> 00:09:36,595
columns, we call the matrix full rank.

237
00:09:38,595 --> 00:09:41,635
Notice, the zero vector will always be included

238
00:09:41,635 --> 00:09:44,410
in the column space since linear transformations must

239
00:09:44,410 --> 00:09:46,170
keep the origin fixed in place.

240
00:09:46,890 --> 00:09:48,570
For a full rank transformation,

241
00:09:48,730 --> 00:09:50,490
the only vector that lands at the origin

242
00:09:50,490 --> 00:09:52,250
is the zero vector itself.

243
00:09:52,490 --> 00:09:54,490
But for matrices that aren't full rank, which

244
00:09:54,490 --> 00:09:56,875
squished to a smaller dimension, you can have

245
00:09:56,875 --> 00:09:59,115
a whole bunch of vectors land on zero.

246
00:10:01,915 --> 00:10:04,075
If a two d transformation squishes space onto

247
00:10:04,075 --> 00:10:06,395
a line, for example, there is a separate

248
00:10:06,395 --> 00:10:09,035
line in a different direction full of vectors

249
00:10:09,035 --> 00:10:10,555
that get squished onto the origin.

250
00:10:11,700 --> 00:10:14,100
If a three d transformation squishes space onto

251
00:10:14,100 --> 00:10:16,180
a plane, there's also a full line of

252
00:10:16,180 --> 00:10:17,940
vectors that land on the origin.

253
00:10:20,580 --> 00:10:22,900
If a three d transformation squishes all of

254
00:10:22,900 --> 00:10:24,925
space onto a line, then there's a whole

255
00:10:24,925 --> 00:10:27,085
plane full of vectors that land on the

256
00:10:27,085 --> 00:10:27,805
origin.

257
00:10:33,165 --> 00:10:35,085
This set of vectors that lands on the

258
00:10:35,085 --> 00:10:37,565
origin is called the null space or the

259
00:10:37,565 --> 00:10:40,180
kernel of your matrix. It's the space of

260
00:10:40,180 --> 00:10:42,660
all vectors that become null in the sense

261
00:10:42,660 --> 00:10:44,500
that they land on the zero vector.

262
00:10:45,540 --> 00:10:47,860
In terms of the linear system of equations,

263
00:10:47,940 --> 00:10:50,260
when v happens to be the zero vector,

264
00:10:50,260 --> 00:10:51,860
the null space gives you all of the

265
00:10:51,860 --> 00:10:53,620
possible solutions to the equation.

266
00:10:56,695 --> 00:10:58,775
So that's a very high level overview of

267
00:10:58,775 --> 00:11:01,095
how to think about linear systems of equations

268
00:11:01,095 --> 00:11:02,055
geometrically.

269
00:11:02,295 --> 00:11:04,615
Each system has some kind of linear transformation

270
00:11:04,615 --> 00:11:07,255
associated with it. And when that transformation has

271
00:11:07,255 --> 00:11:09,710
an inverse, you can use that inverse to

272
00:11:09,710 --> 00:11:10,750
solve your system.

273
00:11:12,430 --> 00:11:13,230
Otherwise,

274
00:11:13,310 --> 00:11:15,630
the idea of column space lets us understand

275
00:11:15,630 --> 00:11:17,470
when a solution even exists.

276
00:11:18,030 --> 00:11:19,870
And the idea of a null space helps

277
00:11:19,870 --> 00:11:21,630
us to understand what the set of all

278
00:11:21,630 --> 00:11:23,070
possible solutions can look like.

279
00:11:25,125 --> 00:11:27,125
Again, there's a lot that I haven't covered

280
00:11:27,125 --> 00:11:29,685
here, most notably how to compute these things.

281
00:11:29,765 --> 00:11:31,205
I also had to limit my scope to

282
00:11:31,205 --> 00:11:33,525
examples where the number of equations equals the

283
00:11:33,525 --> 00:11:34,725
number of unknowns.

284
00:11:35,045 --> 00:11:36,325
But the goal here is not to try

285
00:11:36,325 --> 00:11:38,240
to teach everything, it's that you come away

286
00:11:38,240 --> 00:11:41,440
with a strong intuition for inverse matrices, column

287
00:11:41,440 --> 00:11:44,240
space, and null space, and that those intuitions

288
00:11:44,240 --> 00:11:46,160
make any future learning that you do more

289
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:46,880
fruitful.

290
00:11:47,680 --> 00:11:50,075
Next video, by popular request, will be a

291
00:11:50,075 --> 00:11:52,235
brief footnote about non square matrices,

292
00:11:52,395 --> 00:11:53,675
then after that I'm going to give you

293
00:11:53,675 --> 00:11:55,675
my take on dot products and something pretty

294
00:11:55,675 --> 00:11:57,355
cool that happens when you view them under

295
00:11:57,355 --> 00:11:59,275
